{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492373"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:26:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:26:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1040"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1040"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.56,0.12,0.08,0.15,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1040"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110555"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1040","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1040"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1040"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92812"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1857"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1950"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5837"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14053"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40422"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41598"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110555"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for routine follow-up four months after radical prostatectomy for prostate cancer. The tumour was staged as T3bN1M0 with a Gleason score of 4 + 4 and a pre-operative PSA of 5.0 ng/mL (0-4). Histopathology revealed involvement of the left seminal vesicle and a microscopic deposit in one of seven lymph nodes. He has no significant other medical history and takes no regular medications. He is a retired accountant and lives with his wife.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His surgical wound has healed well. His current PSA is \u0026lt;0.02 ng/mL.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate monitoring plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repeat PSA in six months","Pelvic MRI at twelve months postop","Abdominal CT at six months postop","Clinical review in 3-6 months without further tests","PET scan at 12 months postop"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFollowing radical prostatectomy for prostate cancer, patients require long-term surveillance to detect potential recurrence. The primary method of monitoring is through serial prostate-specific antigen (PSA) measurements, therefore \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat PSA in six months\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate monitoring strategy. Guidelines recommend PSA testing every three to six months for the first two years, then every six to 12 months for the next three years, and annually thereafter. An undetectable PSA (\u0026lt;0.02 ng/mL) at four months post-operatively is reassuring but does not eliminate the need for ongoing surveillance, particularly given this patient\u0027s high-risk pathological features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClinical review without further tests\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate monitoring for a patient with high-risk prostate cancer. Despite the current undetectable PSA, the presence of seminal vesicle invasion and lymph node involvement places this patient at significant risk for recurrence, necessitating ongoing biochemical surveillance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic MRI \u003C/strong\u003Eis not indicated for routine surveillance after radical prostatectomy. Imaging is typically reserved for patients with biochemical recurrence (PSA \u22650.2 ng/mL) or clinical symptoms suggesting recurrence. In the absence of a rising PSA, routine imaging exposes patients to unnecessary radiation and healthcare costs without improving outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal CT \u003C/strong\u003Eis similarly inappropriate for routine post-prostatectomy surveillance. CT scanning would only be considered if there were clinical suspicion of metastatic disease or if PSA levels were rising significantly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPET scan in 12 months\u003C/strong\u003E is not part of routine surveillance following radical prostatectomy. PET scanning is indicated only when there is biochemical recurrence with PSA levels suggesting possible metastatic disease (typically PSA \u0026gt;10 ng/mL) or when patients develop symptoms suggestive of bone metastases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients who have undergone radical prostatectomy for prostate cancer require long-term monitoring with serial PSA measurements.","An undetectable PSA (\u003C0.02 ng/mL) after radical prostatectomy suggests complete tumour removal, but ongoing surveillance is essential given the high-risk features.","PSA monitoring is the primary surveillance tool after radical prostatectomy, not imaging studies."],"references":["Resnick MJ, Lacchetti C, Bergman J, Hauke RJ, Hoffman KE, Kungel TM, Morgans AK, Penson DF. Prostate cancer survivorship care guideline: American Society of Clinical Oncology Clinical Practice Guideline endorsement. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25667275/","Bigarella MP, Floberg JM, Jarrard D. Multidisciplinary management of nonmetastatic locally advanced prostate cancer (t3-4n0m0). Surgical Oncology Insight. 2025;2:100137. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3735210/","Payne H. Management of locally advanced prostate cancer. Asian J Androl. 2009 Jan;11(1):81-7. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3735210/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92812"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1040"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92812"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-01T14:34:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-03T10:45:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1040"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110555"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relat